ram that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nGiven a 2D grid of 0s and 1s, return the number of elements in the largest square subgrid that has all 1s on its border, or 0 if such a subgrid doesn't exist in the grid.\\r\n\\r\n \\r\nExample 1:\\r\n\\r\n\\r\nInput: grid = [[1,1,1],[1,0,1],[1,1,1]]\\r\nOutput: 9\\r\n\\r\n\\r\nExample 2:\\r\n\\r\n\\r\nInput: grid = [[1,1,0,0]]\\r\nOutput: 1\\r\n\\r\n\\r\n \\r\nConstraints:\\r\n\\r\n\\r\n\t1 <= grid.length <= 100\\r\n\t1 <= grid[0].length <= 100\\r\n\tgrid[i][j] is 0 or 1\\r\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def largest1BorderedSquare(self, grid: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def largest1BorderedSquare(self, grid: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        if not grid or not grid[0]:\n            return 0\n        \n        rows, cols = len(grid), len(grid[0])\n        horizontal = [[0] * cols for _ in range(rows)]\n        vertical = [[0] * cols for _ in range(rows)]\n        \n        # Fill the horizontal and vertical arrays\n        for i in range(rows):\n            for j in range(cols):\n                if grid[i][j] == 1:\n                    horizontal[i][j] = horizontal[i][j-1] + 1 if j > 0 else 1\n                    vertical[i][j] = vertical[i-1][j] + 1 if i > 0 else 1\n        \n        # Find the largest square with 1s on its border\n        max_side = 0\n        for i in range(rows-1, -1, -1):\n            for j in range(cols-1, -1, -1):\n                if grid[i][j] == 0:\n                    continue\n                side = min(horizontal[i][j], vertical[i][j])\n                while side > max_side:\n                    if horizontal[i-side+1][j] >= side and vertical[i][j-side+1] >= side:\n                        max_side = side\n                    side -= 1\n        \n        return max_side * max_side\n\n# Example usage:\n# sol = Solution()\n# print(sol.largest1BorderedSquare([[1,1,1],[1,0,1],[1,1,1]]))  # Output: 9\n# print(sol.largest1BorderedSquare([[1,1,0,0]]))  # Output: 1\n```\n\nThis solution first constructs two auxiliary 2D arrays, `horizontal` and `vertical`, where `horizontal[i][j]` represents the number of consecutive 1s to the left of (and including) position `(i, j)`, and `vertical[i][j]` represents the number of consecutive 1s above (and including) position `(i, j)`. \n\nThen, it iterates over the grid from bottom-right to top-left, checking for the largest possible square subgrid with 1s on its border. The size of the square is determined by the minimum of the horizontal and vertical counts at each position, and it checks if such a square can be formed by verifying the horizontal and vertical counts at the opposite corners of the square. The maximum side length of such a square is kept track of, and the area of the largest square is returned.", "estimated_date": 1564272000000}